      "message": "```\ntemplate\u003ctypename _Tp\u003e\n      [[__gnu__::__always_inline__]]\n      inline _Tp*\n      start_lifetime_as(void* __p) noexcept\n      {\n  #if __glibcxx_is_implicit_lifetime \u003e\u003d 202302L\n        static_assert(is_implicit_lifetime_v\u003c_Tp\u003e);\n  #endif\n        auto __q \u003d reinterpret_cast\u003c_Tp*\u003e(__p);\n        __asm__ __volatile__(\"\" : \"\u003dg\" (__q), \"\u003dm\" (*__q)\n                             : \"0\" (__q), \"m\" (*__q));\n        return __q;\n      }   \n```\n\nthis is what it looks like for me in the definition.\nFor placement new it is like this:\n```\n  // Default placement versions of operator new.\n  _GLIBCXX_NODISCARD _GLIBCXX_PLACEMENT_CONSTEXPR\n  void* operator new(std::size_t, void* __p)\n    _GLIBCXX_TXN_SAFE _GLIBCXX_USE_NOEXCEPT\n  { return __p; }\n```\n\nin both cases there is no instruction but in the `start_lifetime_as` there is some hint for the compiler regarding the memory and that it may now contain other data or other type (since we are interpreting it as something different).\n\nI do not think there will be a difference to the case above where the types involved are the same and `start_lifetime_as` is already used.\n\nEven the controlflow is the same, first copy assignment into the `response` object then branching on the first byte of payload and possibly returning `response` object.\n\ni would like to provide a clearer reasoning but at the moment i don\u0027t know how to produce it.\n\nBecause of the inline asm hints it seems kind of hard to achieve the \nsame output asm or even same intermediate representation with \n`-fdump-tree-optimized` even in very simple examples of placement-new vs. start_lifetime_as.\n\nI believe reasoning by similarity to the nearly identical handling in the first case (line 15) is sufficient for this patch but happy to discuss further. For now i will rely on maintainer\u0027s review..",
